On Sunday 07 January 2001 08:41, Adam Carrano wrote:

> I think it doesn't make sense !
> Even if it works why will you buy an expensive Voodoo5 card if
> it works as a Voodoo 3 ?

It doesn't work this way. The Voodoo 3 to 5 are quite similar in 2D but quite 
different in 3D. 

The Voodoo 4 is (as has been said a thousand times before) the only viable 
solution since it offeres significant quality improvements over the Voodoo 3 
(32 bit rendering for example). It all depends however on the documentation. 
We are trying to get this, but that might pose a problem.

> For 2D i'm not sure if the Voodoo5 is really faster than a Voodoo3
> at least for our CPUs and our AmigaOS.
> Windows need fast 2D cards because it is slow, not our Workbench ;)

That is not really a problem of the OS speed. Its a significant different if 
you can use a fast or a slow blitter, and this doesn't have anything to do 
with Windows. Especially if your application does e.g. a lot of rectangle 
moving, like an MPEG player, or requires a good YUV overlay (again like an 
MPEG player)... The Voodoo 3 outperforms the Permedia2 here, the CGX Voodoo 3 
driver I have for the GREX prototype already does full overlaying for that, 
and the results are spectacular - you can stretch a window over a 1280x1024 
screen without speed loss.

> Maybe it would be a good thing if Mr Frank Mariak talk
> with the Warp3D team before announcing his 2D drivers for 3D cards.

If you have a look around, you will quickly notice the absence of any non-3D 
card on the market nowadays. There is practically no 2D-only card available 
anymore, and if it is, its some obscure expensive card that no one will 
really have. 

I must say that Frank Mariak was very helpful in developing the Voodoo 3 
driver, and we do have a line of communication. However, it is neither his 
duty nor his intent to limit himself to cards that we intent to support with 
3D drivers, and it is a mistake to conclude that a working 2D driver will 
yield a working 3D driver at any time. I think Frank is doing a good job at 
supporting as much chipsets as possible, which is of course easier than for 
3D drivers, since most chips share common VGA cores.

What people should not do is to draw conclusions between 2D and 3D drivers. 
That does not work.

Regards, Hans-Joerg.
